title: Watch President Donald Trumpâ€™s full 2025 inauguration speech
author: @OmniphonProductions
comment:
"The Golden Age of America begins right now," because his policies will continue to favor _wealthy_ men in their _golden years._  Talking about a crisis of trust, weaponization of government, the radical establishment (contradiction of terms) extracting wealth and power from our citizens, denial of liberty, inflation, the national debt, constitutional rule of law, respect, ending fascism, and being, "...tested and challenged more than any president in our 250-year history," all reveals he is either the most dishonest man in America, or the least self-aware.  Even after winning a second (last) term, he's _still_ lying, selling his _brand,_ because if he told the truth, his acolytes would stop buying his merchandise.

"Make America Great _Again,"_ implies that America's greatest days lie sometime in the _past._  Anyone who believes that, either _lacks_ imagination or _relies_ exclusively on it!
America has yet to realize it's full potential, and policies that inhibit...or even roll back..."Liberty and Justice for _all,"_ can only serve to deter making America _greater!_

As for Trump's, "...mandate," and claim of, "...unification," behind the Republican Agenda, the majority of voters _didn't_ vote for him.  He won a _plurality_ of the popular vote, beating Harris by _less than 2%_ of the total vote count, _but_ between Harris, RFK Jr., and other third party or write-in candidates, the collective majority of Americans voted for _somebody other than Trump._  He received more votes than any other individual candidate, and he won the Electoral College.  He _is_ the President, but a unified mandate...no!

Regarding the, "Revolution of Common Sense," it's important to remember that any individual's notion of Common Sense is reflective of their own level of education and life experience.  Common Sense is a phrase people use when they mean, "In accordance with my own preconceptions," which often rooted in willful, self-serving ignorance!  When Trump said, "I love the poorly educated," it wasn't a compliment; it was because poorly educated (or systematically mis-educated) people tend to be more _gullible!_  On a related note, I would have thought that a man with a Bachelor's Degree in Economics would understand how tariff's and deficit spending actually work...or don't work!

I will give him credit for one thing.  He's guaranteed to fulfill _some_ campaign promises!  Ending the federal policies of, "...trying to socially engineer race and gender into every aspect of public and private life," or subjecting military personnel to, "...radical political theories and social experiments," will be easy to do.  Just don't do the thing that already isn't being done...like targeting _innocent_ political opponents for _unjustified_ prosecution.  Meanwhile, he'll reinstate military personnel who objected to the COVID vaccine, _while_ again expelling military service personnel for being LGBTQ+ (violating Title VII of the Civil Rights Act, according to the very same Supreme Court _he_ stacked).  Speaking of the military, will our success also be measured by the wars we don't _promote_ by emboldening foreign leaders who would attack and oppress their neighbors (and own citizens)?

HOW DARE HE take credit for the release of the hostages in Gaza as though he had anything to do with those months-long negotiations, especially after (as just mentioned) emboldening a regime that continues to systematically oppress an already marginalized demographic group to the point of violent response...only for that same regime then use that violence as an excuse to spend more than a year killing tens of thousands of civilians, more than half of whom were children.

As for the Gulf of Mexico, Denali, and the Panama Canal, his policies will (1) do absolutely nothing to improve life for Americans and/or (2) violate international law.  As pertains to my second paragraph, returning things to how they used to be...just because they used to be that way...isn't just a waste of energy; it's _illegal_ in many cases.  We can't take back the Panama Canal (or annex Greenland) without committing an act of war.  Changing the names of geographic features won't affect the price of gas or groceries, but it _will_ require educational institutions to spend money on updated textbooks!  How much will it cost _taxpayers_ to replace History and Geography texts in every public school, and what's the point if every _other_ nation in the world is not obligated or legally compelled to acknowledge the changes anyway?  Wasted money, wasted energy, wasted air!

Hearing him utter the phrase, "Manifest Destiny," literally turned my stomach.  Considering how many millions of people have died because of that philosophy, why does anyone think America needs to, "...increase our territory," when so many of our _current_ citizens don't have adequate food, shelter, or medical care.  If you want to make America great, direct your _own_ billions at _that_ problem...and implore your fellow billionaires to do the same...before spending _our_ tax dollars economic imperialism.  What's the point of, "...growing your business," if the employees you already have can't pay their bills?

Side Note: It's incredibly revealing to see members of self-described _news_ organizations in the audience...not with cameras, microphones, notepads, or a shred of journalistic integrity, but as sycophantic propagandists whose networks have paid hundreds of millions of dollars in penalties for _knowingly_ perpetuating lies on his behalf!

I genuinely hope his presidency proves successful _for the American people._  Unfortunately history indicates that his primary...if not only...priority is himself.

comment:
One day soon, those who originally stood truth to power during Don's first term (and beyond), but who are now yielding to fear or self-interest, may come to regret their inaction.

I am deeply disappointed in America today.

I haven't felt this disheartened by America since Bush and his legion of minions silenced the true and accurate majority of voices in 2000.

Personally, I still question the events of 9/11. How might the world have unfolded differently if Gore had been where he was rightfully meant to be?

Don has frightened, bullied, manipulated, bribed, and bought his way back into the very House he turned upside down and inside out during his first term.

How is that different from what happened in 2000? If it's not, what might lie ahead for America?

Those of us who are attuned to reality already know that our system has devolved into a hodgepodge of oligarchy, autocracy, plutocracy, and theocracy, with millionaire and billionaire technocratsâ€”who have major stakes in the gameâ€”helping to make the key decisions.

Am I forgetting anything?

Oh yes, democratic governance. It's still limping along for now, but how long will that last if the complete militarization and securitization of government take hold?

If that happens, what then? Will pesky journalists, dissenters, and members of Congress start showing up poisoned? Accidentally falling from windows? Perhaps the troublesome ones will simply vanish, with no fuss and no mess.

In his first term, Don boasted that he could shoot people in broad daylight and not lose a single vote. Recently, he subtly incited his mysterious group of willing extremists to shoot through crowds of journalists. You know, those shadowy figures who don't existâ€”until they somehow materialize.

It's a chilling reality that we've become numb to the implications of his rhetoric. As the walls close in, those who once held power in the name of democracy now stand silent, complicit, or too afraid to speak out. The lines between fact and fiction, between right and wrong, are so blurred that it's hard to discern where the truth lies anymore.

And so, we find ourselves in a precarious position, questioning not only our present but our future as well. Will we continue down this path, or will the voices of reason and justice rise again before it's too late? The answer remains uncertain, but one thing is clear: the stakes have never been higher. The future of America, and perhaps the world, hinges on the choices we make in the coming days. Will we reclaim the ideals that once defined us, or will we succumb to the forces that seek to dismantle everything we hold dear? The time to act is now.
